    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen 'scrolloff' has a non-zero value (e.g., 1) and the cursor is on a fold and the user presses `zb` or `z-`, the 1st line of the buf is not scrolled to, although it could be scrolled to while maintaining the cursor at the current line. Scrolling instead with `<C-y>` reveals the 1st line.\n\nI see this same behavior in vim 9.1, however I decided to first open the bug report here in nvim since I do not know if nvim handles folds differently and so might need changes not applicable to vim. Please let me know if I should instead report this in vim for the change to be later brought to nvim as a patch.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `nvim --clean`\n\n2. Put this in the buffer:\n\n```\n1\n2\n3\n4\n5\n\nfoo{{{\nbar}}}\n\nbaz\n```\n\n3. `:set foldmethod=marker`. You should see a fold created containing the lines foo and bar. This bug is not specific to foldmethod=marker. You may use instead the foldmethod manual, marker or expr (and perhaps the issue is also present with other foldmethods)\n\n4. `:set scrolloff=1`\n\n5. Move the cursor to the fold or the line between the fold and 5, then press `zb` or `z-`\n\nActual behavior (the bug): The uppermost line in the screen shows 2 (the 2nd line of the buf).\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe uppermost line in the screen shows 1 (the 1st line of the buf).\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.11.6\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nyes, vim 9.1\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 26.3\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nkitty 0.46.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\nHomebrew",
